      "section_title": "How to Write a Research Paper",
      "subsection_id": "sec_01_01",
      "subsection_title": "Preparation Before Writing",
      "text": "Section: How to Write a Research Paper\nSubsection: Preparation Before Writing\nTags: writing process, paper structure, efficiency, writer's block\nContent: Emphasizes the importance of having all materials ready before starting to write, comparing it to cooking where ingredients must be prepped in advance. Critical items include findings fully analyzed and finalized, and figures and tables completed and organized. Advises against starting to write the paper before having these core elements ready, as writing should be the final 10% of the project. Warns that starting to write too early leads to confusion and inefficiency.\nKey points: Finalize findings before writing; Complete figures and tables first; Writing is the final 10% of the project; Avoids confusion and inefficiency"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 2,
      "section_id": "sec_01",
      "section_title": "How to Write a Research Paper",
      "subsection_id": "sec_01_02",
      "subsection_title": "Write the Paper Inside Out",
      "text": "Section: How to Write a Research Paper\nSubsection: Write the Paper Inside Out\nTags: writing process, paper structure, efficiency, writer's block\nContent: Stuckler asserts that trying to write the paper linearly from Introduction → Methods → Results → Conclusion is a major mistake and causes writer's block. Instead, start with the Methods section, which is often the easiest to write and helps build momentum. After Methods, write the Results section, focusing on describing your tables, figures, and key findings in a clear and logical order. The goal is to create a coherent narrative centered around your data to show readers and journal editors the story your research tells. This reverse approach helps avoid getting stuck and accelerates progress.\nKey points: Avoid linear writing (Intro → Conclusion); Start with Methods section; Follow with Results section; Create coherent narrative around"
    },
