      "text": "erventions relevant to your field. This structured conclusion provides a strong foundation for the rest of the paper.\nKey points: Write Conclusion before Introduction; Recap key findings succinctly; List limitations transparently to preempt criticism; Explain implications for future research; Outline policy or practical interventions"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 6,
      "section_id": "sec_01",
      "section_title": "How to Write a Research Paper",
      "subsection_id": "sec_01_04",
      "subsection_title": "Write the Introduction Last",
      "text": "Section: How to Write a Research Paper\nSubsection: Write the Introduction Last\nTags: writing process, paper structure, efficiency, writer's block\nContent: The Introduction is often the most difficult part and a major stumbling block. It has a three-part structure: 1. Establish relevance: Explain why the topic matters now, highlighting its current importance broadly or within the field. 2. Identify gaps: Discuss the weaknesses or missing elements in existing literature, supported by a brief literature review citing prior studies. 3. Present your study's value: Clearly articulate how your research addresses these gaps and the unique contribution it makes. Writing the introduction last allows you to tailor it precisely after having clearly defined your methods, results, and conclusions.\nKey points: Write Introduction last; Establish relevance and current importance; Identify gaps in existin"
    },
