      "chunk_id": 10,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
      "section_title": "Literature Review Guide",
      "subsection_id": "sec_02_01",
      "subsection_title": "What is a Literature Review?",
      "text": "Section: Literature Review Guide\nSubsection: What is a Literature Review?\nTags: literature review, research synthesis, PEER system, conceptual framework\nContent: A literature review is likened to catching up with an old friend after many years, where you learn about key developments, challenges, and opportunities from their life. Similarly, a literature review synthesizes key concepts, current knowledge, gaps, debates, and potential contributions within a specific academic field or topic. It provides a snapshot of the state of the art and highlights areas where further research is needed.\nKey points: Synthesizes key concepts and current knowledge; Identifies gaps and debates; Provides snapshot of state of the art"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 11,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
      "section_title": "Literature Review Guide",
      "subsection_id": "sec_02_02",
      "subsection_title": "Step 1: Dive Straight In – Starting Your Search",
      "text": "Section: Literature Review Guide\nSubsection: Step 1: Dive Straight In – Starting Your Search\nTags: literature review, research synthesis, PEER system, conceptual framework\nContent: Avoid 'paralysis by analysis' by starting immediately with exploratory searches, even if you know little about the topic. Use Google Scholar for initial searches to identify top papers and key contributors in your field. Example given: searching 'inequality and health' to retrieve highly cited or recent influential papers. Download PDFs of about 10-15 relevant papers to begin the reading and summarizing process. Note: Systematic reviews require different techniques; a separate video is referenced for that method.\nKey points: Start immediately with exploratory searches; Use Google Scholar for top papers; Download 10-15 relevant papers; Avoid paralysis by analysis"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 12,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
      "section_title": "Literature Review Guide",
      "subsection_id": "sec_02_03",
      "subsection_title": "Step 2: The Strip Method – Extracting Key Information",
      "text": "Section: Literature Review Guide\nSubsection: Step 2: The Strip Method – Extracting Key Information\nTags: literature review, research synthesis, PEER system, conceptual framework\nContent: Create a Word document with citations listed for each paper to avoid plagiarism and maintain organization. Carefully read each paper, especially abstracts and key sections, and extract (strip out) relevant points and findings. This initial extraction will look messy but is essential for gathering raw material. Include direct quotes with quotation marks to preserve original meaning and attribution. Summarize: What the authors did, Their findings, Suggestions for future research, Contradictory evidence if present. This phase also helps you begin to identify patterns and structure emerging from the literature.\nKey points: List citations to avoid plagiarism; Extract relevant points and findings; Include dire"
    },
