      "subsection_title": "Step 2: The Strip Method – Extracting Key Information",
      "text": "from the literature.\nKey points: List citations to avoid plagiarism; Extract relevant points and findings; Include direct quotes with attribution; Summarize actions, findings, and future research"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 14,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
      "section_title": "Literature Review Guide",
      "subsection_id": "sec_02_04",
      "subsection_title": "Step 3: Develop a Conceptual Framework – Structuring Your Review",
      "text": "Section: Literature Review Guide\nSubsection: Step 3: Develop a Conceptual Framework – Structuring Your Review\nTags: literature review, research synthesis, PEER system, conceptual framework\nContent: The conceptual framework forms the backbone or skeleton of your literature review, organizing the information into a coherent structure. Various approaches to structuring include: Chronological order (useful for historical or developmental topics), Problem-to-solution (progressing from describing an issue to discussing proposed solutions), Levels of analysis (e.g., individual-level evidence followed by population-level evidence), Thematic breakdown (grouping by key themes or debates within the field). After deciding on the structure, use the snowball method to expand your search by following references cited in key papers to find more relevant studies and deepen your review.\nKey points: Framew"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 15,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
