      "subsection_title": "Step 3: Develop a Conceptual Framework – Structuring Your Review",
      "text": "rch by following references cited in key papers to find more relevant studies and deepen your review.\nKey points: Framework forms the backbone of the review; Approaches: Chronological, Problem-to-solution, Levels of analysis, Thematic; Use snowball method to expand search"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 16,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
      "section_title": "Literature Review Guide",
      "subsection_id": "sec_02_05",
      "subsection_title": "Step 4: Writing with the PEER System – Paragraph Structure",
      "text": "Section: Literature Review Guide\nSubsection: Step 4: Writing with the PEER System – Paragraph Structure\nTags: literature review, research synthesis, PEER system, conceptual framework\nContent: The PEER system defines the anatomy of a strong academic paragraph: P (Point): Make one clear, concise claim or topic sentence. E (Evidence/Example): Provide supporting studies or data. E (Explain): Interpret the evidence, explaining its significance. R (Repeat/Link): Reinforce the point or transition smoothly to the next idea. Paragraphs should be clear, focused, and logically linked, building the argument progressively.\nKey points: P: Point (clear claim); E: Evidence (supporting studies); E: Explain (interpret significance); R: Repeat/Link (reinforce or transition)"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 17,
      "section_id": "sec_02",
      "section_title": "Literature Review Guide",
      "subsection_id": "sec_02_06",
      "subsection_title": "Step 5: Conclusion and Introduction Writing Order",
      "text": "Section: Literature Review Guide\nSubsection: Step 5: Conclusion and Introduction Writing Order\nTags: literature review, research synthesis, PEER system, conceptual framework\nContent: Contrary to common practice, write the conclusion before the introduction. The conclusion should include four key components: 1. Summary of findings: Recap the state of knowledge and key insights from the review. 2. Limitations: Discuss weaknesses or gaps either in your review or in the literature itself (e.g., limited papers, methodological weaknesses). This transparency helps anticipate criticism and improve credibility. 3. Future research directions: Suggest areas needing further investigation based on identified gaps. 4. Policy/practice implications: If applicable, propose how findings might inform action or decision-making. The introduction should engage the reader by explaining why the topic matters no"
    },
