      "section_title": "Manuscripts and Publishing Process",
      "subsection_id": "sec_03_10",
      "subsection_title": "Post-Submission Process and Timeline",
      "text": "Section: Manuscripts and Publishing Process\nSubsection: Post-Submission Process and Timeline\nTags: manuscript, publishing, submission, journal selection\nContent: After submission: The author receives a confirmation email with a manuscript ID, confirming the journal has received the paper. The editor reviews the manuscript for suitability. If the manuscript is: Suitable: It is sent for peer review, which can take several months depending on the journal. Not suitable: It is rejected. Upon acceptance: The author receives an acceptance email. The author proofreads and finalizes the manuscript version for publication. The paper is then published within a few days after final proofreading.\nKey points: Receive confirmation email with ID; Editor reviews for suitability; Peer review takes several months; Acceptance leads to final proofreading; Publication within few days after proofing"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 34,
      "section_id": "sec_03",
      "section_title": "Manuscripts and Publishing Process",
      "subsection_id": "sec_03_11",
      "subsection_title": "Post-submission: Evaluation and Decision",
      "text": "Section: Manuscripts and Publishing Process\nSubsection: Post-submission: Evaluation and Decision\nTags: manuscript, publishing, submission, journal selection\nContent: After submission, the journal acknowledges receipt with an acknowledgement letter. The manuscript undergoes peer review by experts, which may take months or longer. Possible editorial decisions communicated to the corresponding author include: Acceptance for publication (with an acceptance letter), Rejection (with a non-acceptance letter), Revision requests: Reviewers may ask for clarifications or additional information; authors revise accordingly. Revisions improve manuscript quality, and this process may repeat multiple times before final acceptance.\nKey points: Acknowledgement letter received; Peer review by experts; Decisions: Acceptance, Rejection, Revision; Revisions may repeat multiple times"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 35,
      "section_id": "sec_03",
      "section_title": "Manuscripts and Publishing Process",
      "subsection_id": "sec_03_12",
      "subsection_title": "Final Stage: Publication and Galley Proof",
      "text": "Section: Manuscripts and Publishing Process\nSubsection: Final Stage: Publication and Galley Proof\nTags: manuscript, publishing, submission, journal selection\nContent: Once accepted, the manuscript is professionally edited and formatted according to the journal's style. Authors receive a galley proof—a near-final version for proofreading. Authors must carefully check for: Spelling errors, Missing pages or content, Correct placement of figures, tables, and text. Any errors or omissions must be reported immediately for correction. After approval of the galley proof by both parties, the manuscript is officially published as a research paper.\nKey points: Professional editing and formatting; Receive galley proof; Check for spelling, missing content, placement; Report errors immediately; Official publication after approval"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 36,
      "section_id": "sec_04",
      "section_title": "Manuscript Writing and Structure (IMRD)",
      "subsection_id": "sec_04_01",
      "subsection_title": "IMRD Structure of Scientific Manuscripts",
      "text": "Section: Manuscript Writing and Structure (IMRD)\nSubsection: IMRD Structure of Scientific Manuscripts\nTags: IMRD, scientific writing, manuscript structure, six S's\nContent: Introduction: Explains the rationale and why the research question was pursued. Methods: Describes what was done to answer the research question in detail. Results: Presents the findings without interpretation. Discussion: Interprets the findings, putting them into context and meaning.\nKey points: Introduction: Rationale; Methods: What was done; Results: Findings without interpretation; Discussion: Interpretation and context"
    },
