      "subsection_title": "Finalizing the Manuscript",
      "text": "Section: Manuscript Writing and Structure (IMRD)\nSubsection: Finalizing the Manuscript\nTags: IMRD, scientific writing, manuscript structure, six S's\nContent: Finalizing the manuscript by adding essential supplementary information: Title page (authors, affiliations, word count). Cover letter. Funding source declaration. Conflict of interest statement. Author contributions (adhering to ICMJE criteria). Appendices and supplementary files. Acknowledgments for contributors not qualifying for authorship. The lecture stresses plagiarism checks before submission to ensure originality and ethical compliance.\nKey points: Add Title page, Cover letter, Funding declaration; Include Conflict of interest and Author contributions; Add Appendices and Acknowledgments; Perform plagiarism checks"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 47,
      "section_id": "sec_04",
      "section_title": "Manuscript Writing and Structure (IMRD)",
      "subsection_id": "sec_04_09",
      "subsection_title": "Scientific Writing Style and Six S's",
      "text": "Section: Manuscript Writing and Structure (IMRD)\nSubsection: Scientific Writing Style and Six S's\nTags: IMRD, scientific writing, manuscript structure, six S's\nContent: To articulate content effectively, the lecturer recommends: Use simple, specific, and necessary words. Maintain consistent terminology. Use inclusive and non-offensive language, as some journals require explicit statements about this. Use precise word order and avoid passive voice. Keep sentences concise, avoiding long or convoluted structures. Submit manuscripts for scientific language editing (grammar, spelling, punctuation, structure) by professionals or specialized software. The lecture highlights the 'six S's' of scientific writing as guiding principles: Simple (Use straightforward language), Short (Keep sentences and text concise), Structured (Follow a clear organizational format), Sequential (Logical flow of ideas)"
