      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_01",
      "subsection_title": "How Peer Reviewers Are Found",
      "text": "Section: Writing Peer Review Reports\nSubsection: How Peer Reviewers Are Found\nTags: peer review, reviewer guide, evaluation, feedback\nContent: This is a common question — editors find reviewers by: Looking at who published similar papers recently, Checking who is cited in the submitted paper, Using databases like Publons or Web of Science, Personal professional networks. Researchers can also volunteer to review on platforms like Publons (Clarivate). Communities by Field: PubMed/ MEDLINE (medical and life sciences), IEEE Xplore (engineering and technology), SSRN (social sciences, economics, law), PhilPapers (philosophy), ERIC (education research).\nKey points: Editors find reviewers via similar papers, citations, databases; Researchers can volunteer on Publons; Field-specific communities: PubMed, IEEE, SSRN, etc."
    },
    {
