      "text": "nts and complements the overall review process.\nKey points: State background and expertise; Establish credibility; Mention structure and any de-emphasized aspects; Helps editors contextualize comments"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 54,
      "section_id": "sec_05",
      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_04",
      "subsection_title": "Step 3: Structuring the Main Sections of the Review",
      "text": "Section: Writing Peer Review Reports\nSubsection: Step 3: Structuring the Main Sections of the Review\nTags: peer review, reviewer guide, evaluation, feedback\nContent: Two common ways to structure the main body of a review: 1. Chronological approach: Provide feedback on each section of the paper (introduction, literature review, methods, results, etc.). 2. Thematic approach (recommended): Organize the review around major points of criticism instead of following the paper's structure. The video strongly advises against the chronological method, stating it is not the approach used by experienced reviewers. Suggested structure involves identifying about 3 to 6 main points of critique, each given roughly equal attention. Example of main points: Theoretical motivation of the study, Lack of transparency in method description, Missing theoretical contribution.\nKey points: Avoid Chronological appr"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 55,
      "section_id": "sec_05",
      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_04",
      "subsection_title": "Step 3: Structuring the Main Sections of the Review",
      "text": "tudy, Lack of transparency in method description, Missing theoretical contribution.\nKey points: Avoid Chronological approach; Use Thematic approach (recommended); Identify 3-6 main points of critique; Give equal attention to each point"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 56,
      "section_id": "sec_05",
      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_05",
      "subsection_title": "Step 4: Constructive Criticism",
      "text": "Section: Writing Peer Review Reports\nSubsection: Step 4: Constructive Criticism\nTags: peer review, reviewer guide, evaluation, feedback\nContent: For each main point, structure your critique into three parts: 1. Positives — Start by noting what you liked about the paper related to this point. This balances the review and acknowledges the authors' efforts. 2. Negatives — Clearly state your criticisms, specifying exact parts of the text to help authors locate issues. 3. Suggestions for Improvement — The most crucial element; offer concrete, actionable advice to improve the paper. Suggestions can include: Recommending additional literature, Proposing stronger arguments, Suggesting methodological changes. Emphasizes the importance of remaining objective and constructive rather than harsh or overly negative.\nKey points: Structure: Positives, Negatives, Suggestions; Acknowledge authors' efforts"
    },
