      "chunk_id": 58,
      "section_id": "sec_05",
      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_06",
      "subsection_title": "Step 5: Minor Points",
      "text": "Section: Writing Peer Review Reports\nSubsection: Step 5: Minor Points\nTags: peer review, reviewer guide, evaluation, feedback\nContent: Minor points are smaller issues noticed during reading, such as: Linguistic inconsistencies, Citation errors. Create a brief list of these, including page references. Example: If too many minor errors exist, do not list all individually; instead, make a general comment recommending professional proofreading. Clarifies that the reviewer is not a proofreader but should point out persistent issues.\nKey points: List minor issues (linguistic, citations); Include page references; Recommend professional proofreading if many errors; Reviewer is not a proofreader"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 59,
      "section_id": "sec_05",
      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_07",
      "subsection_title": "Step 6: Including References in Your Review",
      "text": "Section: Writing Peer Review Reports\nSubsection: Step 6: Including References in Your Review\nTags: peer review, reviewer guide, evaluation, feedback\nContent: A professional review includes a short reference list citing sources used to support critique or recommendations. This practice helps authors easily access the literature you mention and facilitates addressing your points. Including references elevates the review from mediocre to very good by demonstrating scholarly rigor and thoroughness. Encourages reviewers to make it as easy as possible for authors to implement suggestions.\nKey points: Include short reference list; Cite sources supporting critique; Demonstrates scholarly rigor; Helps authors implement suggestions"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": 60,
      "section_id": "sec_05",
      "section_title": "Writing Peer Review Reports",
      "subsection_id": "sec_05_08",
      "subsection_title": "Step 7: Recommendation",
      "text": "Section: Writing Peer Review Reports\nSubsection: Step 7: Recommendation\nTags: peer review, reviewer guide, evaluation, feedback\nContent: The reviewer must provide a recommendation about the paper's fate: Reject, Major revisions required, Minor revisions required, Accept as is. The recommendation is typically not included directly in the review text to simplify the editor's task of summarizing multiple reviews. The final decision lies with the editor, not the reviewer. Even if recommending rejection, the reviewer's critique should be constructive and helpful since authors still benefit from the feedback.\nKey points: Provide recommendation (Reject, Revise, Accept); Do not include recommendation in review text; Final decision lies with editor; Critique should be constructive even if rejecting"
    }
